Input.posts:
A quick question regarding suspensions, is it possible to approach them by step also in some situations, or is it always (without exception) necessary to have the exact same note as a preparation note?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Andi. Sorry for not being able to reply earlier! I'm not sure if I'm understanding your question correctly, but I think what you're trying to say is that if it's possible for the NCT suspension to be left the same or 'left lying' instead of resolving it down a step into the next chord tone.  Well, if this is what you mean, then my answer to you is that the NCT suspension should always resolve to the next chord tone by that stepwise approach. Otherwise, it wouldn't be called a suspension 4-3, suspension 7-6 or a suspension 9-8!

Hello, this is John the bassist. Just want to say I'm still plodding along and keeping up with the theories presented as well as could be expected. The main issue i'm having is that being a non piano player 'and' a non computer notation guy, when Mr. Edwards starts cutting pasting transposing and moving notes around here and there I get left in the dust in a hurry! I've downloaded Finale Note Pad but that is also very frustrating. Up till now I'm doing all the exercises and assignments the old fashioned way with paper and pencil. I guess what i'm asking is that maybe you could also provide XML files for the exercises like you have for the actual musical examples so that us low tech guys have a chance to keep up to speed and follow along with Mr. Edwards in a similar fashion of how he is presenting the lesson materials, on a computer notation program? Otherwise I'm absolutely loving the class. Thanks for considering.... John

Hello, this is John the bassist. Just want to say I'm still plodding along and keeping up with the theories presented as well as could be expected. The main issue i'm having is that being a non piano player 'and' a non computer notation guy, when Mr. Edwards starts cutting pasting transposing and moving notes around here and there I get left in the dust in a hurry! I guess what i'm asking is that maybe you could also provide XML files for the exercises like you have for the actual musical examples so that us low tech guys have a chance to keep up to speed and follow along with Mr. Edwards in a similar fashion of how he is presenting the lesson materials, on a computer notation program? Otherwise I'm absolutely loving the class. Thanks for considering.... John

In lesson 5 Dr Edwards notes that the descending 5 6 progression is that used by Pachelbel. In the second to last chord Dr Edwards disallows the leading tone b as the melody, but if my memory is correct, Pachelbel does use this note. presumably he is voicing in 4voices so has more flexibility? or am i wrong? how would you voice to get the b?
Upvotes:
1
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Kim. You're right, that about clears it up. What Dominic pointed out with Pachelbel's cannon makes all that difference with Dr. Edwards' example, except that Pachelbel's Cannon is descending 5-6 progression, but with Dr. Edwards' example, inversions are used with the progression to smoothen out the bass line.
